{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FNz2FohXrXwgBLitssk7y3","type":"tool_result","content":"# ray/job_submission\n# Fix the Ray job script to connect to the correct head address and print \"pong\"\n\nprompt: |\n  A Ray cluster is running, and the ray-client pod contains a job script at\n  /opt/job.py. The job should connect to the head service and print \"{{params.expected_output}}\".\n\n  Current issue: the script uses the wrong head address and fails to connect.\n\n  Your task:\n  - Update the job script so it connects to ray-head:6379.\n  - Ensure the job runs successfully and prints \"{{params.expected_output}}\".\n\n  You can test with:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl -n ray exec ray-client -- python /opt/job.py\n  ```\n\n  Success criteria: the command exits 0 and prints \"{{params.expected_output}}\".\n\nparams:\n  expected_output:\n    default: pong\n    description: String the Ray job is expected to print on success\n\nnamespace_contract:\n  required_roles: []\n\nmetrics:\n  - time_to_first_mutation\n\npreconditionUnits:\n  - name: ray_env_ready\n    on_probe_fail: skip\n    probe:\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray get pods 2>/dev/null | grep -c Running\"\n        timeout_sec: 10\n    apply:\n      - command: \"kubectl create namespace ray\"\n        sleep: 0\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-head-service.yaml\"\n        sleep: 1\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-head.yaml\"\n        sleep: 2\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray rollout status deploy/ray-head --timeout=120s\"\n        sleep: 2\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-worker.yaml\"\n        sleep: 2\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray rollout status deploy/ray-worker --timeout=120s\"\n        sleep: 2\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-job-script.yaml\"\n        sleep: 1\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-client.yaml\"\n        sleep: 1\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray wait --for=condition=Ready pod/ray-client --timeout=60s\"\n        sleep: 1\n    verify:\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray get pods 2>/dev/null | grep -c Running\"\n        timeout_sec: 10\n\n  # Additive fixture unit (Rule 4): the oracle execs `python /opt/job.py` inside\n  # ray-client. Standalone, ray_env_ready's apply provides the ray-job-script\n  # ConfigMap and a ray-client that mounts it at /opt/job.py. But in a workflow\n  # this case usually inherits a live cluster from a prior stage (deploy/scale/\n  # upgrade), whose ray-client pod does NOT mount the job script and whose apply\n  # is skipped here -- so /opt/job.py is missing and the oracle cannot run. This\n  # unit ensures JUST that fixture idempotently: it (re)creates the job-script\n  # ConfigMap and, if /opt/job.py is absent, recreates ONLY the throwaway\n  # ray-client client pod with the mount. It never touches the head/worker\n  # cluster state or the namespace. The probe gates on the script being present,\n  # so standalone (script already there) it is a harmless no-op.\n  - name: job_script_ready\n    on_probe_fail: skip\n    probe:\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray exec ray-client -- test -s /opt/job.py 2>/dev/null && echo present\"\n        timeout_sec: 15\n    apply:\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-job-script.yaml\"\n        sleep: 1\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray delete pod ray-client --ignore-not-found=true --wait=true\"\n        sleep: 1\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-client.yaml\"\n        sleep: 1\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray wait --for=condition=Ready pod/ray-client --timeout=60s\"\n        sleep: 1\n    verify:\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray exec ray-client -- test -s /opt/job.py 2>/dev/null && echo present\"\n        timeout_sec: 15\n\noracle:\n  verify:\n    commands:\n      # The oracle execs the Ray client job, whose first connection to the cluster\n      # (ray://...) is legitimately slow on a cold cluster; 60s was too tight and\n      # could fail a correct fix. Allow 150s.\n      - command: \"python3 cases/ray/job_submission/oracle/oracle.py\"\n        timeout_sec: 150","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0cbccc33-96d1-4e87-848b-98bc2521a62d","uuid":"cbcd1335-e353-435e-b50a-2edb5cede386","timestamp":"2026-06-15T01:32:22.209Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"# ray/job_submission\n# Fix the Ray job script to connect to the correct head address and print \"pong\"\n\nprompt: |\n  A Ray cluster is running, and the ray-client pod contains a job script at\n  /opt/job.py. The job should connect to the head service and print \"{{params.expected_output}}\".\n\n  Current issue: the script uses the wrong head address and fails to connect.\n\n  Your task:\n  - Update the job script so it connects to ray-head:6379.\n  - Ensure the job runs successfully and prints \"{{params.expected_output}}\".\n\n  You can test with:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl -n ray exec ray-client -- python /opt/job.py\n  ```\n\n  Success criteria: the command exits 0 and prints \"{{params.expected_output}}\".\n\nparams:\n  expected_output:\n    default: pong\n    description: String the Ray job is expected to print on success\n\nnamespace_contract:\n  required_roles: []\n\nmetrics:\n  - time_to_first_mutation\n\npreconditionUnits:\n  - name: ray_env_ready\n    on_probe_fail: skip\n    probe:\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray get pods 2>/dev/null | grep -c Running\"\n        timeout_sec: 10\n    apply:\n      - command: \"kubectl create namespace ray\"\n        sleep: 0\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-head-service.yaml\"\n        sleep: 1\n      - command: \"kubectl -n ray apply -f cases/ray/job_submission/resource/ray-head.yaml\"\n        sleep: 2\n      - command: \"